Mapping renewable resources and power generation

The EIA maintains detailed data on power generation from power plant reporting, including wind- and solar-powered electricity generation. These data are available here by year. Well load in some packages and then grab the data from 2019 to start looking at current energy trends.

library(tidyverse)
library(curl)
library(readxl)
library(maps)
EIA860query <- "https://www.eia.gov/electricity/data/eia860/archive/xls/eia8602019.zip"
EIA860fp <- "./EIA860_2019.zip"

curl_download(EIA860query, EIA860fp, quiet=TRUE)
dir.create("./EIA860_2019")
unzip(EIA860fp, exdir = "./EIA860_2019")

These files come in .XLSX form, so well use the tidyverse package readxl to read the data into R. Our primary interest is the generators contained in 3_2_Wind_Y2019.XLSX and 3_3_Solar_Y2019.XLSX, but 2__Plant_Y2019.XLSX has the information we need to localize position of the generators in terms of latitude and longitude. We can join the plant-level data to the generator-level data using the Plant Code column.

wind19 <- read_excel("./EIA860_2019/3_2_Wind_Y2019.xlsx", skip = 1)
solar19 <- read_excel("./EIA860_2019/3_3_Solar_Y2019.xlsx", skip = 1)
plant19 <- read_excel("./EIA860_2019/2___Plant_Y2019.xlsx", skip = 1)

wind19loc <- left_join(wind19, plant19, by="Plant Code")
solar19loc <- left_join(solar19, plant19, by="Plant Code")

The wind and solar data files have a ton of detailed information on the generators. If youre following along with this tutorial, spend a little time exploring the data and understanding the relationships between the variables. For now, lets look at the location of wind and solar power generators in the contiguous US. We could just plot the points using latitude and longitude, but it would be more helpful to plot them on top of a map of the US so we can see what areas of the country are using these technologies. For that, well use map_data from ggplot2 to get the outlines of the states. We can plot the states with geom_polygon and the plants with geom_point. Make sure to include group=group in the aesthetics for geom_polygon or youll get strange lines crisscrossing the country.

states <- map_data("state")
colors <- c("wind" = "blue", "solar" = "gold")

ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = states, aes(long, lat, group=group), color = "black", fill = "white") +
  geom_point(data = solar19loc, aes(Longitude, Latitude, color="solar"), alpha = 0.1) +
  geom_point(data = wind19loc, aes(Longitude, Latitude, color="wind"), alpha= 0.1) +
  coord_fixed(1.3) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(-125, -65)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits=c(25, 50)) +
  labs(x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude", color = "Power source") +
  scale_color_manual(values = colors)

There are some interesting trends here. Wind-generated power seems to be concentrated in the middle of the country, while solar power seems more coastal. It could have to do with the distribution of wind and solar resources, so lets add that information to our analysis. The National Renewable Energy Laboratory in Colorado provides detailed spatial grids of both solar and wind energy across the US. There are lots of options to choose from, but for now, well use the annual average Direct Normal Irradiance (DNI) and the annual average wind speed at 100m above surface level (see here and here for more information or from the citations below). Note that these raster files are quite large. We will also load in some packages specifically designed to handle this type of geospatial data.

# Sengupta, M., Xie, Y., Lopez, A., Habte, A., Maclaurin, G., & Shelby, J. (2018). 
# The national solar radiation data base (NSRDB). Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews, 89, 51-60.

# Draxl, C., B.M. Hodge, A. Clifton, and J. McCaa. 2015. 
# Overview and Meteorological Validation of the Wind Integration National 
# Dataset Toolkit (Technical Report, NREL/TP-5000-61740). Golden, CO: National Renewable Energy Laboratory.

# Draxl, C., B.M. Hodge, A. Clifton, and J. McCaa. 2015. 
# "The Wind Integration National Dataset (WIND) Toolkit." Applied Energy 151: 355366.

# Lieberman-Cribbin, W., C. Draxl, and A. Clifton. 2014. 
# Guide to Using the WIND Toolkit Validation Code (Technical Report, NREL/TP-5000-62595). 
# Golden, CO: National Renewable Energy Laboratory.

# King, J., A. Clifton, and B.M. Hodge. 2014. 
# Validation of Power Output for the WIND Toolkit (Technical Report, NREL/TP-5D00-61714). 
# Golden, CO: National Renewable Energy Laboratory.

dni_url = "https://www.nrel.gov/gis/assets/data/nsrdbv3_dni.zip"
curl_download(dni_url, "DNI.zip", quiet=TRUE)
dir.create("./DNI")
unzip("DNI.zip", exdir = "./DNI")

wind_url = "https://www.nrel.gov/gis/assets/images/us-wind-data.zip"
curl_download(wind_url, "windspeed.zip", quiet=TRUE)
dir.create("./windspeed")
unzip("windspeed.zip", exdir = "./windspeed")

Lets start by reading the DNI raster and converting it into a dataframe that ggplot2 can work with.

library(raster)
library(viridis)
library(maptools)
library(sp)
library(ggthemes)

dni <- raster("DNI/nsrdbv3_dni/Annual DNI/nsrdb3_dni.tif")
dni_df <- as.data.frame(dni, xy = TRUE)

ggplot() +
  geom_raster(data = dni_df , aes(x = x, y = y, fill = nsrdb3_dni)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c() +
  coord_quickmap()

Thats a good looking map! But for this analysis, were only interested in the contiguous US, so well need to apply a mask to the raster to set the values of everything outside the US to NA. The raster package provides a very easy to use function mask, and we can get the shape of the US from maps::map. That will give us the shape of the US which we can convert to a Spatial Polygon (the format required by mask). To do this conversion, we need to provide the appropriate proj4 projection for our map. Fortunately, in this case, the projection is easy: the map was provided to us with latitude and longitude, just like our generator locations.

usa <- map("state", fill=TRUE, plot=FALSE)
IDs <- sapply(strsplit(usa$names, ":"), function(x) x[1])
usa <- map2SpatialPolygons(usa, IDs=IDs, proj4string=CRS("+proj=longlat +datum=WGS84"))
usaraster <- mask(dni, usa)

usaraster_df <- as(usaraster, "SpatialPixelsDataFrame")
usaraster_df <- as.data.frame(usaraster_df)
colnames(usaraster_df) <- c("value","x","y")

ggplot() +
  geom_raster(data = usaraster_df, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = value)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c() +
  coord_quickmap()

Thats more like it! Now we can add in our previous geoms of state lines and solar power generators to get the final map.

ggplot() +
  geom_tile(data=usaraster_df, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = value)) +
  geom_polygon(data = states, aes(long, lat, group = group), color = "black", fill = NA) +
  geom_point(data = solar19loc, aes(Longitude, Latitude), alpha = 0.2, stroke = 0, shape = 16, color = "white") +
  scale_fill_viridis(na.value="white") +
  coord_fixed(1.3) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(-125, -65)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(25, 50)) +
  theme_map() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom",
        legend.key = element_rect(fill = "gray"),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold")) +
  ggtitle("Average annual DNI and distribution of solar-powered generators") +
  labs(fill = "DNI")

California seems to be taking advantage of high annual DNI, but many of the hotspots of solar power generation arent in the areas of peak DNI. In fact, they seem to follow state boundaries more closely than the availability of solar radiation, suggesting state-level policy may play an important role in the construction of solar-powered generators.

But what about wind?

The process should be very similar, but not all rasters follow a consistent format. When we try to read in the windspeed data, R gives us the helpful hint that our data seems to be flipped along the y axis!

windspeed <- raster("windspeed/wtk_conus_100m_mean_masked.tif")
data seems flipped. Consider using: flip(x, direction='y')
windspeed_df <- as.data.frame(windspeed, xy = TRUE)

Fortunately, their recommendation of flip fixes that problem.

wind <- flip(raster("windspeed/wtk_conus_100m_mean_masked.tif"), direction = 'y')
wind_df <- as.data.frame(wind, xy = TRUE)

ggplot() +
  geom_raster(data = wind_df , aes(x = x, y = y, fill = wtk_conus_100m_mean_masked)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c() +
  coord_quickmap()

But now, take a look at the x- and y-axes. Those numbers dont seem like the latitudes and longitudes that we were using before, and the upper edge of the US isnt straight across like it was in the previous plot. These data were provided in a Lambert Conformal Conic projection! A full discussion of projections is beyond the scope of this tutorial, but it is good to know that the raster package provides a projectRaster function that allows us to convert between projections. That means we can turn this into the lat/long projection weve been using. In this case, the coordinate reference system (crs) command "+init=espg:4326" is asking for a projection into the same WGS84 latitude/longitude system we were using previously.

wind_latlong <- projectRaster(wind, crs="+init=epsg:4326")

usawind <- mask(wind_latlong, usa)
usawind_df <- as(usawind, "SpatialPixelsDataFrame")
usawind_df <- as.data.frame(usawind_df)
colnames(usawind_df) <- c("value","x","y")

ggplot() +
  geom_raster(data = usawind_df, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = value)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c() +
  coord_quickmap()

Now we can finish up our analysis of wind patterns and wind turbines.

ggplot() +
  geom_tile(data=usawind_df, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = value)) +
  geom_polygon(data = states, aes(long, lat, group = group), color = "black", fill = NA) +
  geom_point(data = wind19loc, aes(Longitude, Latitude), alpha = 0.2, stroke = 0, shape = 16, color = "white") +
  scale_fill_viridis(na.value="white") +
  coord_fixed(1.4) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(-125, -65)) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(25, 50)) +
  theme_map() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom",
        legend.key = element_rect(fill = "gray"),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold")) +
  ggtitle("Average annual windspeed and distribution of wind generators") +
  labs(fill = "Wind speed (m/s)")

Here we see a much different pattern than solar power. Wind-powered generation seems to cluster specifically in areas with relatively high windspeeds and does not seem confined to state boundaries, suggesting that wind power is driven primarily by the availability of the wind resource and not state-level policy.
